Introduction to Machine Learning - Term Project¶

Nilay Kamar¶

Nowadays, social media has been a tool in which people can say their opinions about everything. These posts can be generally related to actual news, their likes, thoughts, suggestions, hate, etc. If these posts can be analyzed, companies would get insights from them to use in their campaigns or customer segmentation studies.

Both touching the social point and developing myself on text mining, I chose to analyze tweets contain given hashtags. We have witnessed many upsetting things as a Turkish in the last decade. My purpose of the term project is to analyze the sentiment of these tweets and extract some insights from them.

Because of the lack of turkish text mining studies corresponding to english, there are a huge challenging work area to study on term project. I have been used well known libraries to see how the model can be developed.

About the data¶

Because of the restrictions of the Twitter API to get tweets posted in older than seven days, I used to library shows on Github repository to get all tweets posted on since 01.01.2010 until 01.05.2020. To get user information of these tweets, I benefited from Twitter API. the library which I used in getting tweets, searching tweets with given filters, reading HTML pages, and writing them on CSV files. I got tweets with filters contains different hashtags, and save them on a given folder.

Firstly, I combined all CSV files in the given folder, and store them data frame object.

Firstly, it should be done preprocessing on the dataset. Preprocessing is the hardest part of a machine learning project, however, text mining is also challenging because of being unstructured. Converting turkish characters, extracting additional features, conversion of timestamp to date format can be counted as parts of preprocessing. Removing urls, picture links, and mentions is an essential for tweets datasets.

In [3]:
def preprocessing(df):
    #drop duplicates
    df = df.drop_duplicates(subset=None, keep='first', inplace=False)
    df = df.drop_duplicates(subset= "text", keep='first', inplace=False)
    #convert turkish characters
    conversionTable = str.maketrans("ğĞıİöÖüÜşŞçÇ", "gGiIoOuUsScC")
    df["text"] = df["text"].apply(lambda x: x.translate(conversionTable))
    df['text'] = df['text'].apply(lambda x: " ".join(x.lower() for x in x.split()))
    #extract date, hour, and day features of tweets
    df["date"] = df["date"].apply(lambda x: datetime.datetime.strptime(x, '%Y-%m-%d %H:%M'))
    df["tweet_hour"] = pd.to_numeric(df["date"].apply(lambda x: x.strftime("%H")))
    df["day"] = df["date"].apply(lambda x: x.strftime("%A"))
    #extract hashtags and create a new column
    df["hashtag"] = df['text'].apply(lambda x: re.findall(r'\B#\w*[0-9A-Za-z]+\w*', x)) 
    df["text_modified"] = df['text'].apply(lambda x: re.sub(r'\B#\w*[0-9A-Za-z]+\w*', '', x)) #modified tweets
    #extract pictures and create a new column
    df["pictures"] = df['text'].apply(lambda x: re.findall('\S*twitter.com\S*', x))
    df["text_modified"] = df['text_modified'].apply(lambda x: re.sub('\S*twitter.com\S*', '', x)) #modified tweets
    #extract url and create a new column
    df["url"] = df['text'].apply(lambda x: re.findall(r'https?:\/\/.*[\r\n]*', x)) 
    df["text_modified"] = df['text_modified'].apply(lambda x: re.sub(r'https?:\/\/.*[\r\n]*', '', x)) #modified tweets
    #extract mentions and create a new column
    df["mentions"] = df['text'].apply(lambda x: re.findall(r"(?:\@|https?\://)\S+", x)) 
    df["text_modified"] = df['text_modified'].apply(lambda x: re.sub(r"(?:\@|https?\://)\S+", '', x, flags=re.MULTILINE)) #modified tweets
    #extratc punctuations
    df["text_modified"] = df['text_modified'].apply(lambda x: re.sub('[^\w\s]', '', x)) #modified tweets
    #removing numbers
    df["text_modified"] = df['text_modified'].apply(lambda x: re.sub('\d', '', x)) #modified tweets
    #removing redundant spaces
    df["text_modified"] = df["text_modified"].apply(lambda x: x.strip().replace("  ", " "))
    df["text_modified"] = df["text_modified"].apply(lambda x: x.strip().replace("   ", ""))
    return df

def count(df):
    lst = df["id"]
    df["text_len"] = [len(df.loc[df["id"] == i]["text_modified"].to_string().replace("  ", " ")) for i in lst]
    df["word_count"] = [len(str(df.loc[df["id"] == i]["text_modified"].to_string().replace("  ", " ")).split(" ")) for i in lst]
    return df
df = count(df)

### Stopwords, Lemmatization, Tokenization

The words which do not change the meaning of sentence even if they are extracted are named as stopwords. While mining text, removing them provide more clear text to generate feature and model. Therefore I used nltk library to remove stopwords from tweets. Trstop is also an example of removing stopwords in turkish.

In [54]:
w2v_model = Word2Vec(min_count=20,
                     window=2,
                     size=300,
                     sample=6e-5, 
                     alpha=0.03, 
                     min_alpha=0.0007, 
                     negative=20,
                     workers=multiprocessing.cpu_count()-1)



start = time()

w2v_model.build_vocab(sentences, progress_per=50000)

print('Time to build vocab: {} mins'.format(round((time() - start) / 60, 2)))

Time to build vocab: 0.04 mins
  • min count = 3 - remove most unusual words from training embeddings, like words 'ssssuuuuuuuppppppeeeeeerrrr', which actually stands for 'super', and doesn't need additional training
  • window = 4 - Word2Vec model will learn to predict given word from up to 4 words to the left, and up to 4 words to the right
  • size = 300 - size of hidden layer used to predict surroundings of embedded word, which also stands for dimensions of trained embeddings
  • sample = 1e-5 - probability baseline for subsampling most frequent words from surrounding of embedded word
  • negative = 20 - number of negative (ones that shouldn't have been predicted while modeling selected pair of words) words that will have their corresponding weights updated while training on specific training example, along with positive word

#Most frequently occuring words
def get_top_n_words(corpus, n=None):
    vec = CountVectorizer().fit(corpus)
    bag_of_words = vec.transform(corpus)
    sum_words = bag_of_words.sum(axis=0) 
    words_freq = [(word, sum_words[0, idx]) for word, idx in      
                   vec.vocabulary_.items()]
    words_freq =sorted(words_freq, key = lambda x: x[1], 
                       reverse=True)
    return words_freq[:n]
#Convert most freq words to dataframe for plotting bar plot

def create_tfidf_dictionary(x, transformed_file, features):
    '''
    create dictionary for each input sentence x, where each word has assigned its tfidf score
    
    inspired  by function from this wonderful article: 
    https://medium.com/analytics-vidhya/automated-keyword-extraction-from-articles-using-nlp-bfd864f41b34
    
    x - row of dataframe, containing sentences, and their indexes,
    transformed_file - all sentences transformed with TfidfVectorizer
    features - names of all words in corpus used in TfidfVectorizer

    '''
    vector_coo = transformed_file[x.name].tocoo()
    vector_coo.col = features.iloc[vector_coo.col].values
    dict_from_coo = dict(zip(vector_coo.col, vector_coo.data))
    return dict_from_coo

def replace_tfidf_words(x, transformed_file, features):
    '''
    replacing each word with it's calculated tfidf dictionary with scores of each word
    x - row of dataframe, containing sentences, and their indexes,
    transformed_file - all sentences transformed with TfidfVectorizer
    features - names of all words in corpus used in TfidfVectorizer
    '''
    dictionary = create_tfidf_dictionary(x, transformed_file, features)   
    return list(map(lambda y:dictionary[f'{y}'], x.text_modified.split()))

def replace_sentiment_words(word, sentiment_dict):
    '''
    replacing each word with its associated sentiment score from sentiment dict
    '''
    try:
        out = sentiment_dict[word]
    except KeyError:
        out = 0
    return out

Results - What I learned for my capstone project?¶

This project is done with simple and well-known text processing techniques, even if it is known these are not well worked in Turkish texts. It can be counted learnings from this project below:

  • Preprocessing is still the most important part of modeling. Libraries developed for English do not fit properly to Turkish text as shown above. Therefore, libraries developed for Turkish sentiment should be used.
  • Numbers should be removed before modeling. However, numbers corresponding to date could be important for topic classification in tweet mining. So, these numbers should be converted to text before modeling. They were removed in this project.
  • People have not been pay attention to grammar rules while posting a tweet. To get a more clear dataset, the conversion of social text to a proper one should be done. For example, "olmaaaaaz" should be converted to "olmaz".
  • Spelling errors should be fixed before modeling. For instance, "slm" should be converted to "selam".
  • There are still some text processing problems such as redundant space. This causes calculating wrongly word count or text length features.
  • The some part of dataset may be labeled manually, then, supervised learning applied on datasets. This way may be time consuming, however, it would be help to develop more accurate model.
